Pubnum: B-reps  
Abstract: A typical B-rep describes a solid in its full detail. Collision detection algorithms that locally analyze the B-rep of non-convex objects usually process the entire B-rep due to the lack of spatial ordering of its topological entities. For very complex objects, this global processing is time consuming. It is also unnecessary. One approach in avoiding the global processing is to use several B-reps of different levels of detail. However, this does not always help. For instance, when objects in close proximity need to be analyzed for contact, the need for a local increase in resolution forces a global increase in detail. Our solution is to unify the different levels of detail and provide the means to locally control them. We introduce a locally resolvable B-rep (LRB-rep) as a non-manifold B-rep data structure with locally varying levels-of-detail for representing complex objects. The LRB-rep locally hides the solid's details with several layers of faces. A subset of all the faces provides a global approximation of this solid. We call this the wrapper. The wrapper starts with the faces of the LRB-rep's outer-most layer and, controlled by some application, may change its shape. Local face refinements reveals more detail and eventually resolve the wrapper to the original object with the highest level of detail. A two-body collision detection algorithm can use the LRB-reps as follows. Instead of checking the complex boundaries of both solids, the wrapper of one solid can be checked against the wrapper of the other solid. The wrapper faces that interpenetrate can be refined and recursively checked. Faces that do not interpenetrate can be ignored in further checking and not refined. The motivations behind the LRB-rep design are 1) to check as few face pairs as possible when detecting collisions between two complex objects in close proximity; 2) to avoid fragmentation caused by the use of some hierarchical approaches such as the BSP and the MSP trees during classification and 3) to overcome various other limitations of hierarchical approaches, such as the octrees or the MSP trees. In this paper we introduce the LRB-rep, the wrapper and its operations, prove several properties, provide empirical results based on our implementation, and suggest its use for the n-body problem. 
